'''Homerism''' is a word to describe the activity of [[mime|miming]] of scenes from one of [[Homer]]'s epics. It was common in [[Ancient Greece|Greek]] and [[Ancient Rome|Roman]] era [[paganism|pagan]] [[festivals]], along with other displays of virtuosity such as juggling, acrobatics and trumpet blowing.

'''Homerism''' also applies to a new [[figure of speech]] named after the cartoon character [[Homer Simpson]]. It denotes an expression that reveals more than the speaker intended.

